305. Tokai J Exp Clin Med. 1990 Mar;15(1):87-92.

Concurrent murine cytomegalovirus and Klebsiella pneumoniae infections in 
germfree mice.

Tazume S(1), Umehara K, Leung WC, Ando K, Hata J, Hashimoto K.

Author information:
(1)Department of Microbiology, School of Medicine, Tokai University, Kanagawa 
Japan.

The effects of concurrent murine cytomegalovirus (MCMV) and Klebsiella 
pneumoniae infections were studied in germfree (GF) mice. The mice received 
sublethal doses, 5 x 10(5) pfu, of MCMV. K. pneumoniae was injected in doses of 
40 to 100 cfu, which by itself killed 0-33% of GF mice. When K. pneumoniae was 
given to GF mice infected with MCMV, the mortality increased up to 100%, with 
distinct enhancement persisting until day 10 of the MCMV infection. The virus 
titer in various organs did not change after superinfection with K. pneumoniae, 
while the viable counts of K. pneumoniae in organs remained remarkably high 
until death, suggesting the cause of death to be severe generalized infection by 
the bacteria. When compared to specific pathogen-free (SPF) mice, GF mice were 
more susceptible to both MCMV and K. pneumoniae infection, had higher titers of 
the virus for longer periods in various organs, and showed extension in the 
duration of enhanced mortality by the bacteria. Histopathologically, the spleen 
and liver were found to be the most severely affected tissues, more so in GF 
than in SPF mice, with recovery from the changes being slower in the GF animals.

