334. Am J Public Health. 1991 Jan;81(1):79-84. doi: 10.2105/ajph.81.1.79.

The impact of HIV-related illness on employment.

Yelin EH(1), Greenblatt RM, Hollander H, McMaster JR.

Author information:
(1)Department of Medicine, University of California, San Francisco.

We used structured telephone interviews to determine the extent of work loss 
following onset of symptoms, the interval between onset of symptoms and 
cessation of work, and the risk factors for work loss among 193 persons with 
symptoms of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV)-related illness attending the 
AIDS Clinic at the University of California, San Francisco, between October 1, 
1988, and September 30, 1989. Estimates of the duration of time between onset of 
HIV-related symptoms and work loss derive from the life table method of Kaplan 
and Meier. A Cox proportional hazards model is used to estimate the effect of 
risk factors on the probability of withdrawing from work in each time interval. 
Eighty-six percent of the respondents worked prior to onset of the first symptom 
of HIV-related illness; 40 percent were working at the time of the most recent 
interview, a mean of 958 days later. The total number of hours worked declined 
by 59 percent during this time. Kaplan-Meier analysis indicates that 50 percent 
who worked prior to onset of HIV-related illness stopped working within two 
years and all had stopped within 10 years after onset of the first symptom.

DOI: 10.2105/ajph.81.1.79
